{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_bentley_ver01/data/sn86088122/00200297659/1908040201/1017.xml":{"full_text":"\"1\nV\nTHE WEEKLY HERALD. APRIL 2, 1908.\n8\nLOOKING TO\nAMARILIO\nCommission Men and Others\nTake Interest In Cattle\nraisers Convention\n(From Thursdays Dally\nWishing Amarlllo every micron In\nJior effort to entertain t crowd.\"\nBays Chcrry-Tildcn compauy of Kuu\ntas City, ouo of the commUnlon flriua\n(hlrh has written to Chairman Tom\nJ4. Miller of the committee on deco\nration fr tho \"mlng convention of\nthe I'anhnndlo t attle lUlsora' asso\nciation, and moreover tho firm pins\nthe custoniury cheek for 12' to\nIt letter to pay for an advertising\ncard on one of the big Illuminated\nrrhr-s which will he erected on the\nstreet In honor of the cattlemen and\ntt friend.\nI ioin Mauf Center.\nFrom every one of tho livestock\nrenters which draw from the Pan\nhandle aro coming ulimlar letters and\nimllar remittance. Thompnon-Dlnkard-Unimert\ncompany. South St.\nJohepu. If. Thl Co.. Kansas City,\nFrank Wltberapoon, Kantian City and\nulsewbere, are noine of the firms\nwhose cards, aro bring made. Tarn\nhljn A Co., of Kansas City. Is \"glad\n1o help the association and Kind to\njet the opportunity for putting our\nme \"before tho people\" and backs\nup the statement iiceordlngly. tfavns-finlder-Buel\ncompuny Is not. content\nwith putting Its card on one of the\nrchei but wants a space on all five\nrcaes which the committee Is now\nplanning to erect.\nIVrt Worth and the ranliandlc.\n\"The Interests of Fort Worth and\nrf the ranhandlo ure Identical,\" Is\nIbe legend which Captain B. B. Tad\ndock sends to be featured on one of\nthe arches for the Fort Worth Board\net Trade, and tho captain also adds\nthat \"It will afford me great pleas\nure to be with you on that occasion,\nIt my business engagements will per\nmit.\" Since (business Is the only\npo.glblo bar to his being In Amarlllo,\nthe cheerful duty now devolves on\nthe captain's some hundreds of Tan\nhandle friends to make a lot of busi\nness engagements here for him on\nthose dates.\nRig Outside Attendance,\n\"I havo been talking Panhandle\nconvention at Fort Worth and at San\n'Antonio aud wherever else I've been\nlately,\" said William Penn Aaderaou,\nlivestock agent of tho Southern Kan\nsas, this morning, \"and from all I\nhear, this convention Is going to\nhavo the biggest attendance from\noutside its territory that It ever had.\nTraders for the Northwest business\nam going to be here, There was\npot a great deal of trading- at tho\nother conventions and 1 look for a\ngood deal of business here during the\nPanhandle convention. Then too\nthere is golns to be a \"bigger at\ntendance than ever before from Kan\nsas city, St. Joe, Chicago, Fort Worth\nend the packing centers, of commis\nsion men and others who are luter\nrated directly or indirectly In the\nrattle business.\"\nUnderwood for City Attorney,\nIt. E. Underwood who announces\ntoday as candidate for the office of\ncity attorney, .Is Junior member of\nthe law firm of Veale. Haztewood\nUnderwood. He has now been a cit\nizen of Amarillo for about two years\nand to become a partner la tho law\nfirm here he resigned tbo posltlou\nef attorney In Jack county, at Jack\naonboro. lie announces uow for the\noffice of city attorney at the re\ntiqest of citizens and propert owners\nhere who believe that a man of his\nexperience will bo able to best safe\nguard the city's interests, Amarlllo\nhas just grow0 out of the small town\nclass and Into tho class of cities and\nthe problems with which the city\ngovernment will bavo to deal in\ngranting and regulating franchises,\nand in the adjustment of affairs with\npublio service corporations of all\nkinds requires the constant co-op\neration jof ft skilled and experienced\nlegal advisor, It Is this feature of\nthe oJflce which Mr. Underwood em\nphasizes and on a platform of effi\nciency in the performance of his du\nties If elected, he respectfully solicits\nthe support and suffrage of citizens\nat the election, April 7.\nW. L Thompson for Alderman.\nIn announcing as a candidate for\nre-election to thy office of alderman\nof tho city f Amarlllo. W. T. Thomp\nyjn does so at tho request of citizens\nwho have watched hla work for the\ncity during tho put two years and\nwho believe that ihn rxperlcucu he\nbus acquired and thn Judgment hn\nhas shown muko him one ef the\nanient men that can lie chosen tor the\nposition. Mr. Thompson In one of\nthe oldent cltUens cf Amarlllo In\ntlnio of rehldoncfi here and his largo\nInterests are almost, wholly In the\ndty of Amarlllo. lie hiis therefore\n11 personsi Inierest In the municipal\naf fair which niaken hint, whether In\nor out of office, Intent on securing\nan econumlcul and progressive ml\nministration of thn city's ufalrs. Me\naccordingly invite the support, of\nthe citizens at the polls In the elec\ntion April 7 and pledges if elected,\ntho sumo active aud constant atten\ntion to the duties of bio office dur\ning; the next term as has character\nized bis work during the present\nterm.\nKnickerbocker Rank lle-Opeued.\nNew York, Mar. 28. Marking an\nother decided step toward the return\nof prosperity ti the metropolis, the\nKnickerbocker Trust Company,\nwhich closed Its doors last October,\nwas re-opened for business today.\nThe bank has asseU of over jO.OOd,\n000. with liabilities slightly less, and\nthere Is every likelihood It will be\nable to pay all of tho 20,000 deposi\ntors In full.\nThe reopening of thn Knickerbock\ner Trust. Company In accordance ith\nplans for its rehabilitation, prepared\nafter four months' labor by a com\nmittee of depositors, released to the\ncommunity assets aggregating $46.\n370,620. \"The reopening of the Knicker\nbocker Trust company,\" declared\n.lames Russell Seoly of the counsel\nfor tho depositors' committee, \"will\nhavo a stimulating effect not only\nupon thn local financial situation,\nbut upon every financial center on\nthe globe.. It Is the best thing that\nhas happened since the panic.\"\nJustice Clarke, In dismissing thn\ntemporary receivers of the suspended\ntrust company and signing the re\nsumption order, spoke In commend\natory vein of the work of the de\npositors committee, counsel and oth\ners who had labored so assiduously\nIn working out the rehabilitation\nplan.\nUnder the term of this plan the\ndepositors of the Knickerbocker\nTrust company will not receive their\ndeposits in full when the trust com\npany opens its doors, but will re\nceive 10 per cent today if they want\nIt and the remaining portions of the\ndeposits can be withdrawn at Inter\nvala covering a period of about two\nand one-half years.\nHE \"OVERDREW\"\nHIS BANK AGGNUNT\n(From Thursday's Dally.)\nA chance customer at the Famous\nlate yesterday afternoon who gave\nhis name as J. K. or J. F. Williams,\ngave in payment ou a small purchase\nof merchandise la check lor $20.\nMunuger Sum Isaacs, who had\nwatched the customer closely, went\nto the cashier's desk aud after au\nthorlzlng the payment of the check\nsent a man to follow the stranger\nas he left the store.\nThen a phone message to the bank\non which the check was drawn dis\nclosed the fact that tho follow had\ndrawn out his entire balance amount\nlug to something over $10 Just before\nthe bank closed for thn fnternoon\nThe check which ho had presented\nIn the Famous was of course worth\nless at the bank.\nThis started a lively chase after\ntho customer who was finally over\nhauled at the unlou station walling\nto board one of the outbound trains\nWhen confronted by the store men\nhe quickly returned the $20 for the\nmerchandise and cash which ho got\nat the Famous, and then protested\nthat ho had sinply overlooked the\nfact that his balance at the bunk\nwas not largo enough to cover his\ncheck, of this matter the store men\nrefused to Judgo and the man was\nturned over to tho officers for\nfurther examination of his case,\nObjects In Election.\nWashington, I). C., March 2(5.\nSenator Burrows, chairman of tho\ncommittee on privileges and elections\ntoday objected to tho swearing In\nof Senator-elect Smith of Maryland\nwho was chosen to succeed the late\nSenator Whyfe, on the ground that\nSmith's election had not been In ac\ncordance with the form prescribed by\nthe constitution. There hud been a\nroll call of tho senate just previous\nto this proceeding and almost all\nthe senators were In their seats.\nFROM GOLF\nTO DENVER\nIsland\nTrain\nThrough Amarlllo\nEastern Llmlteds\n(From Thursday's Dally,)\nA new passenger train that will\nxcell anything thus far put on reg\nular schedule through Anmrillo is\nannounced as the result of arrange\nments between the Hock Island and\nFort Worth and Denver manage\nments. Colonel U. F. loaltmum nas\nplanned toward this schedule for\njcars and tho plan Is ibelng finally\nrarrrled Into execution through tho\nagency of W. K. Cireen and D. B.\nKeeler. Of this new train which\nwill put Amarlllo and the Amarlllo\nsummer school In line for the best\npossible train service the Fort Worth\nRecord says:\nGalveston to Dallas.\nThis train service, as Indicated by\nthe events of the past ten days, will\noriginate In Galveston. From Gal\nveston the train will traverse the\nTrinity Brazos Valley to Dallas,\naud at the latter point will pass over\nInto the territory of another Yoa\nkum property, tne Rock Island. The\ntracks of the latter will be toured\nis far as Fort worm, tiers inn\nFort Worth t Denver will receive\nthe train and carry It through the\nPanhandle and deliver it. to the Col\norado L Southern line at Texllne.\nThonre the trip to Denver will te un\nbroken.\nFor Tourist Traffic.\nIt Is obvious that the passenger\ndepartments of the Trinity Bra\nzos Valley, Rock Island, Fort Worth\nDenver and Colorado L Southern\ndesire to Inclndn Dallas and Waxa-\nhachle, on the route on account of\nthe great amount of tourist traffic\nthat comes out of these cities.\nIndications now are that this ser\nvice will be Inaugurated within tlxty\ndays, or just as soon as proper sched\nules can be made out and advertised.\nFor the first few weeks, perhaps,\nonly a sleeper and a day coach will\nbe carried from Oalveston to Denver,\nbut when the summtr tourist season\nopens up this will be increased to a\nfull train handsomely appointed and\nsuperbly equipped. This Gulf to\nRockies train will eventually rival\nthe great overland llmlteds, the\nTwentieth Century of the Lake Shora\nor the Knickerbocker Special of the\nBig Four.\nImproving Roadbed.\nIt will be remembered that the\nTrinity Brazos Valley has been\nputting forth great exertions within\nthe past few months to place the\ntrack In perfect condition, and that\nnext Sunday through day service will\nbe put Into effect by the passenger\ndepartment, it Is also clear that the\nrecent conferences In Fort Worth 'be\ntween Vice president and General\nManager W. K. Green and General\nPassenger Agent Harry P. Bronson\nof tho Trinity Brazos Valley on\nthe one hand and Vice President\nKeeler and General Passenger Agent\nA. A, Gllsson on the other had to do\nwith an Important matter in the pas\nsenger service. Mr. Gllsson also re\ncently paid a visit to Houston, and\nMr. Keeler has just returned from\nDenver, where he met Vice Presi\ndent Parker of the Colorado\nSouthern.\nConvention Travel.\nThe service from Galveston\nthrough Dallas and Fort Worth to\nDenver would make a strong bid for\nthe summer tourist business during\nthe hot months and in the winter\nwould probably bo the great highway\noftravel from the Northwest to tho\nSouth and Southeast.\nIt Is further expected that this\ntrain over tho Yoakum line will bi\nselected by tho southern delegations\nto thn Denver Democratic convention\nIn July.\nThis train will pass over what Is\ncalled the short line mileage be\ntween Denver and Galveston. The\nroute, as will be Been by reference\nto tho map Is almost as straight as\nthe proverbial crow flics, and Is\nmany miles shorter than any other\nline between these, two points. The\nexact distance Is 1,123 tulles, divided\nas follows: Calveston to Fort Worth\n322 miles, and Fort Worth to Denver\n803 miles. The time required to\ncomplete this Journey would be\nabout two days and two nights.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles L. Green are\nback Jorai a trip to Fort Worth.\nMM IW ll'l HI t\nUpon Every Bottloj\nAnd Wreppsr of ths Cenulno\nDr. Cell's PIna-Tar-Honey\nis printed tli bova dtiifD J tbo\nnunilier 06. The SUn I nnr trarto\nmark, and SOt It ear gamnmiy turner.\nTil mxlicine cnouined In mirh tioltl\nwill car Oouf hi, CI1 nnit nil BrnauM!\ntroublna mora quickly auit tDtcttially\nthan any otaar rtiardy.\nDR. DELL'S\nPine -Tar-Honey\nla sold brail druajiau 'Ae., SOt. and $1.00\nprrbottla. ilaaufaotured only by\nTHE E. E. SUTHERLAND MEDICINE CO.\nPatfucih, Ktnlucki,\nletter I'nsigne!.\nCoffeyvllle, Kan., March 26. C\nT. Carpenter, vice president of the\nCondon National Bank of this city,\nreceived a letter today telllns him\nto pay a stranger $3 5 on demand un\nder penalty of having his bank and\nresidence destroyed by dynamite.\nThe letter was unsigned.\n(iliddeu In floly l-nnrt.\nCairo, Egypt. Mar. 26 Charles J.\nGlldden and wife of Boston, are now\nmaking a tour of the Holy Land In\nan automobile. They recently visit\ned Jerusalem and created a profound\nsensation among the residents who\nhad never before seen a motor car.\nTennessee Banker Meet.\nMemphis, Tenn., Mar. 2b For\ntbo first time since 1890, Memphis\nwill be the host of the Tennessee\nBankers' Association. The conven\ntion will extend through three days\nand many financial subjects of im\nportance to Tennessee and the\nSouth will be discussed.\nKILLS TWO HORSES\n(From Thursday's Dally.)\nA cut of four freight cars coining\nfrom a flying switch struck and\nkilled the team of horses attached\nto a Wclls-Fargo express wagon driv\nen by C. J. Yates at the Buchanan\nstreet crossing yesterday evening. By\nthe narrowest margin, tho driver\nescaped serious injury but the horses\nwere killed instantly.\nAt the crossing over Buchanan\nstreet the Rock Island has several\ntracks and on the track which the\nexpress wagon was approaching a cut\nof cars was standing so as to hide\nthe other track from view. Further\ntfp the track ad \"engine was at work\nswitching and the driver saw It slow\ndown on tho track He wits approach\ning so he hurtMed to eroas. But the\nengine Tiad just made a '(lying switch\nand turned four cars loose on the\nother track. Just as the team go?\non the second track, this cut of cars\ncrashed full into them. The necks\nof both the horses were broken by\nthe blow and they were thrown com\npleiely from the track. Yates was\nthrown from the wagon but beyond\nslight, bruises he escaped Injury.\nFlying switches such as caused the\naccident yesterday evening are dis\ncouraged b.V both statute laws and\nrules of the companies but train\ncrews make use of them in order\not save time. Usually, however, they\nare not used outside the yards proper\nor across streets.\nThe railroad company settled In\nfull yesterday with' the express com\npany by the payment of $750 for\nthe damage done.\nMarried ly Justice Holman.\n(From Thursday 'in bally.)\nJustice Holman officiated yester\nday afternoon at the .courthouse at\nthe wedding of W-E. Edward Mouk\nand Miss Mamie J. Baker, two young\npeople who, although they do not\nlive here .are well \"known to many\npeople of Amarillo, Both have beeu\nrepresentatives through iranhandle\nterritory for the Collier Publishing\ncompany and yesterday they arrang\ned that both reach Amarillo at the\nsame time and that the new partner\nship should be formed. Mr. and\nMrs. Mcmk will make their home\nhere.\nBRYAN IS\nWATCHING\nAnti-Bryanlles at Work In East\nand ine Commoner\nVlsils\nWashington. D. C, March 2.6\nrolltlcians attribute a hidden signif\nicance to tho Mult of William Jen\nnings Bryan In Washington today.\nTho establishment of Johnson head\nquarters here and In New York aud\nother eastern cities, and rumors of\na plan to capture in\" rasiern dele\ngations at Denver for the Minnesota\nrusn, have, canoed som trepidation\namong the Nebraskan's supporters\nin Washington. Mr. Bryan will hold\nseveral Important conferences with\nDemocratic leaders In Washington\ntoday.\nTomorrow Mr. Bryan will Invade\nPennsylvania, one of the strongholds\nof the opposition to his caudldacy,\nspeaklug tomorrow evening in Pitts\nburg. Reports state that the mem\nbers of th Pennsylvania Bryan\nleague havo arranged an elaborate\nreception for their chief, and that\nhis appearance In the Smoky City\nwill mark the beginning of a deter\nmined campaign to contest the state\ndelegation In the interest of the Nc-\nbraskan.\nFrom Pittsburg Mr. Bryan will go\nto Parkeriburg, W. Ya.. and thence\nto Kansas City, Mo., where he will\nbe the guest of honor at one of the\ngreatest political banquets ever held\nIn tho West, to bo held Monday\nnight. On Tuesday ho will be in\nLincoln and will entertain the Dem\nocratic and Populist editors of Ne\nbraska at a hRnqucf. Later next\nweek he will begin a western tour\nthat will Include cities and towns In\nKansas, Colorado, Nebraska and\nIowa.\nWhile Mr. Bryan Is engaged In\nswinging around the circle, his op-1\nponents in the East will be busily I\nengaged in manufacturing Johnson\nthunder, In the hope of preventing\nthe Nebraskan's nomination for the\npresidency. Tho antl-Bryanltes hope\nto secure control of the delegations\nfrom New York, Pennsylvania, New\nJersey, Delaware and Massachusetts,\nwith posfibly several others. In New\nYork, the Bryan opposition Is headed\nby Mayor McClellan and Charles F.\nMurphy, while other prominent poli\nticians have taken the lead in other\neastern states. While Johnson la\nconsidering the logical choice of tho\nantl-Bryanitcs. cither .Tudson Har\nmon of Ohio, or Judge Gray of Dela\nware, would be acceptable as a com\npromise. According to report much work\nhas already been quietly done In or\nganizing the anti-Bryan men In Penn\nsylvania. Massachusetts and New Jer\nsey, arS the indications are. it was\nsaid, that the campaign will be a\nhard one for the Bryan men to fight.\nWhile the delegations from tho four\nstates would not constitute a third\nof the whole number a third being\nnecessary to prevent a nomination\nit was slated that the backers of the\nmovement expect that If they can\ncontrol the solid delegations from\nfour important states they will have\nlittle difficulty in rallying other del\negations about them, and In that way\nmussing enough to defeat a nomina\ntion o\" tho first ballot.\nNew York has seventy-eight dele\ngates, Pennsylvania, sixty-eight;\nMassachusetts, thirty-two and New\nJersey, twenty-four, a total of 202.\nThere are 965 votes and Mr. Bryan\nwill have to get 643. To prevent his\nnomination on tho first 'ballot, his\nopponents will have to muster 322\nvotes. It was pointed out by friends\nof the Nebraskan that he has many\nfriends In nil the 8tate mentioned,\nand thai, while tininstructcd dele\ngations might be sent from each to\nthe couventlou. It would hardly be\npossible for the anti-Bryan men to\ncapture all the delegates from each\nof the states. Ou the other hand, It\nwas stated that, with the air of the\nunit rule solid anti-Bryan delegations\nmight be sent to Denver.\nIn promoting their campaign the\nanti-Bryan forces will have the co\noperation of Minnesota, which will\nsend a delegation Instructed for\nJohnson, and of Delaware, which has\nalready signified Its intention of\nsending Its delegates pledged to\nJudge Gray. Massachusetts, through\nlis state committee has refused to\ndeclare for Bryan and North Caro\nlina, to the surprise of the Bryanltes,\nfailed to adopt a Bryan resolution.\nrrrrrt\nfi!XiUsx: Avb fit'-\nIwelieM\nThe Tonic Properties of Old WhisKey\nare recounted ly all physicians of standing -whiskey to be\nmedicinally pure must be the real article such a whiskey it\nSonnyBrooli\nTHE PURE. FOOD\nWhiskey\nIt is distilled in 